# Normalize line endings across platforms. Without this, git's
# `core.autocrlf` setting can interact with prettier on Windows in
# confusing ways: files end up with CRLF on disk while the index stores
# LF, and `prettier --check .` (which reads from disk) flags every file
# as needing formatting even though the committed content is already
# correct. `text=auto eol=lf` tells git to store LF in the index *and*
# check out LF on every platform — one source of truth.

* text=auto eol=lf

# Windows shell scripts must stay CRLF or cmd.exe can misread them.
*.bat text eol=crlf
*.cmd text eol=crlf
*.ps1 text eol=crlf

# Binary blobs — never normalize.
*.png binary
*.jpg binary
*.jpeg binary
*.gif binary
*.ico binary
*.webp binary
*.avif binary
*.pdf binary
*.woff binary
*.woff2 binary
*.ttf binary
*.eot binary
*.otf binary
*.mp4 binary
*.webm binary
*.mp3 binary
*.zip binary
*.gz binary
